ious places called Villars, from Late Latin <i>villare</i> ‘(part of an) outlying farm, dependent settlement’, a derivative of Latin <i>villa</i> ‘country house, estate’ (later used of a group of houses forming a settlement)."]}]},{"name":"Bartholomew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of New Testament origin, the name of an apostle mentioned in all the synoptic gospels (Matthew, Mark, and Luke) and in the Acts of the Apostles. It is an Aramaic formation meaning ‘son of Talmai’, and has been assumed by many scholars to be a byname of the apostle   Nathaniel .  <i>Talmai</i> is a Hebrew name, said to mean ‘abounding in furrows’ (Numbers 13:22)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Bartholomew de Villiers III was born in 1254, in Villiers-le-Sec, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France as the son of Bartholomew de Villiers II. He had at least 2 daughters. He died in 1324, in Cyprus, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1254–1324":"1254–1324","1278–1335":"1278–1335","1278–Female":"1278–Surnud","1226–1276":"1226–1276","1226":"1226","1324":"1324","1335":"1335","1278":"1278","1254":"1254","1276":"1276","Villiers, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Villiers-le-Sec, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Cyprus":"Küpros"},"fi":{"1254–1324":"1254–1324","1278–1335":"1278–1335","1278–Female":"1278–Kuollut","1226–1276":"1226–1276","1226":"1226","1324":"1324","1335":"1335","1278":"1278","1254":"1254","1276":"1276","Villiers, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Villiers-le-Sec, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Ranska","Cyprus":"Kypros"},"fr":{"1254–1324":"1254–1324","1278–1335":"1278–1335","1278–Female":"1278–Décédée","1226–1276":"1226–1276","1226":"1226","1324":"1324","1335":"1335","1278":"1278","1254":"1254","1276":"1276","Villiers, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Villiers-le-Sec, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France","Cyprus":"Chypre","lifeSummary":"Bartholomew de Villiers III est né en 1254, à Villiers-le-Sec, C